title: For Sale/Trade:  Yugo M70 AK-47 (M70B1)
postcontent:
This is a Century International Arms M70 Fixed Stock AK-47 (M70B1) in very near mint condition. 99% of the M70s out there are under-folders and the fixed stock version is hard to find as very few of these were made. The metal is excellent and the wood is very nice. This AK has grenade launching capability and grenade launching sight as shown in the pictures.

The rifle shoots the popular 7.62x39 caliber. It is very accurate, features a threaded muzzle with a slant brake installed Two mil-surp metal 30 round mag's and Green canvas sling,bayonet lug,bayonet and scabbard (number matching) and heavy duty bipod with 200 rounds of Ammo,upgraded Black fore end with UltiMAK M9 optic mount ( Wood Fore end Included ).Barrel: 16 1/4", Overall: 34 1/4".

The rifle is a combination of original Yugoslavian rifle parts and U.S.-made compliance parts. The fit and finish of the rifle is more than acceptable, with an evenly applied Parkerized finish and an above-average-condition wood fore-end.

The M70B1 has some novel features that set it apart from the run-of-the-mill AK variant. First, it has the enlarged and reinforced area around the trunnion like the RPK on its stamped receiver. In addition, a unique grenade ladder sight located on the gas block, when rotated into its upward open position, provides meter range marks and cuts off the gas port in the gas block. Also, the rifle features front and rear flip-up night sights, although the luminous material has long since disappeared. Has a smooth and comfortable trigger.

title: For Trade:  Cub Cadet IH 682 Tractor for trade
postcontent:
picked up this IH built 682 with a badly blown Kohler kt-17 last year. I swapped in a freshly rebuilt (by me with Kohler parts) K-301 12hp from a IH Cub Cadet 1250. I used all the correct 82 series engine mounts for the swap, and it fits perfectly. The electric clutch works perfectly, and lines up correctly, as does the muffler. It starts up and runs very nice. I replaced the hydro pump as the old one had a worn swashplate....so I just replaced the pump, but I do have a good swash plate now to swap into the old pump if someone is interested. I started to adjust the linkages and got it pretty much where it needs to be, but winter set in, and I put it on the back burner so I could get my garage re-arranged for winter. It runs great and drives good..but needs some adjusting of the rods, and linkages. I did also notice that after I first started it up it dripped a little hytran from a seal on the pump.....but it seemed to stop after running it for a while, and now it doesn't leak..possible just dry seals from sitting, I don't know, but it seems good now. 
Sheet metal is all in good shape...normal scratches from tree limbs and such, but no major dents or dings, hood ornament is missing..lights all work, steering is nice and tight, tires are ok..some cracking..but not too bad....it also comes with a mule drive and 44" deck that mows nice..it needs some welding on the runners, but still pretty solid. 

Overall its a great running solid tractor, and I love the 82 series Cub tractors, but I'm itching for something else.  

 Myself and the 682 are located in Macedon, ny 20 miles East of Rochester , Ny  ...drop me an e-mail and we'll take it from there, Trade only please...Thanks! 


Here is a short video of my son driving it after the engine swap this fall.. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GkQenD6demM

title: For Sale/Trade:  CA Legal Polish AK47 M1960 7.62x39 w/detachable mag, bayonet with scabberd
postcontent:
CA Legal Polish AK47 M1960 7.62x39 w/detachable mag, bayonet with scabberd
This is a factory new, unfired, Century Arms Polish M1960 milled AK-47 rifle in the popular 7.62x39mm caliber. The M1960 is built from original first generation AK parts on a new US made milled receiver and with a new proper med-heavy 16" long barrel. This has the original Soviet milled AK look and feel. The AK-47 is perhaps the most famous assault rifle in the world. Prototypes appeared in 1946 and fullscale production had begun by 1951. The original AK used a heavier barrel, milled receiver, silver bolt carrier, bayonet lug under the front sight block, ported gastube, 14mm threaded barrel, and differently shaped furniture. In 1959, Russia switched to the cheaper and lighter AKM, which used a stamped receiver and had a lighter barrel. Poland began making a licensed built copy of the original milled AK in 1960 and this is what this semi-auto rifle is based upon. The M1960 was virtually a clone of the original Soviet AK-47, produced at the famous Radom factory, known for its quality and good fit and finish. The rifle I am selling here is new, unfired. It comes in the original box. It has all the early aK-47 features including 14mm threaded barrel, type I bayonet lug, original laminated furniture, and even the original Polish pistol grip. It comes with 1-10 round magazine, proper bayonet with scabberd and cleaning kit. These are neat rifles for someone wanting an early style of aK, an accurate shooter, or just a fun range toy. Over the last year, the US made ATM milled receiver has prooven to be reliable and durable.  If you have any questions at all, please feel free to contact me
